metadata.name: Quantum Folly #39
metadata.description:
This piece explores humanity's vanity and obsession with controlling natural forces. In the end we are beholden to the whims of the universe and its rules. What we think is artificial is but nature's inclination.

As an atom gazes at the world it can see the arrogant hand of mankind imposing its will. We are nature's inane creation built from imperceptible, discrete particles.

Enjoy watching the structures form. Due to the nature of the system it may take some time to complete. Once it's fully rendered you can download a full resolution image of 3508 x 4961 px by ***double clicking/tapping***. At this size the piece is printable at A3 size at 300 dpi. If you're interested in acquiring a signed print please contact @KRANKARTA.

Features include: palette, orientation, architecture, particle rules, boundary seepage and colour displacement.

Created on Chrome desktop 103.0 on 2022-07-21 in javascript and GLSL. Results on other browsers/devices may vary.

metadata.name: Chord Unknown #12
metadata.description:
The feeling of experimenting with an instrument you have not learned, and then suddenly striking an actual chord.

The code creates several grids and then applies one of six unique deformation techniques with varying intensity. It's a defined process of experimentation, and even though I'm the one that wrote the rules, each output breaks through somehow as a complete surprise to me. So when I see them, I get a Chord Unknown.

Created by Eric Davidson. 2022.

metadata.name: interference x resonance #269
metadata.description:
M: "Have you noticed that every day is like every other day, somewhat?" 

T: "Yes, I've noticed that" 

M: "And have you noticed that every week is more or less like every other week?" 

T: "Yes..."

M: "Well, did you know that every day has a relationship to four other days. And they are not the four days preceding it. They are scattered back through time. One of them may be six months in the past, one of them may be thousands of years in the past, but each day is actually an interference pattern caused by the resonant... the coming together of the resonances of other times."

T: "...I mean... it's a weird idea. It NEVER occurred to me that that was a possibility."

-- Terence McKenna, ethnobotanist, psychonaut, and noted boundary-pusher

The story above was an inspiration for this generative artwork. To me, art is about communicating ideas, ideas that sometimes fall outside of the boundaries of our normal, culturally-sanctioned model of reality. 

This work is about the interconnectedness of all things. It's about the repeating patterns and echoes, both seen and unseen, that impact the world around us and our experience of it. How things are always the same and yet not the same, different and yet not different. And it's a reminder to always question what you think you know.

metadata.name: Matter Waves #15
metadata.description:
If light, which is generally a wave, can also sometimes be a particle - then can matter also be a wave? Louis De Broglie suggested this idea, which is supported by performing a double slit experiment with matter particles and producing an interference pattern that indicates wave behaviour. Performing the experiment with one particle at a time also produces an interference pattern, implying the particles create interference with themselves. One way this could be possible is if the particle travels infinite potential paths simultaneously, super positioning itself in many places at once. If one electron can be in infinite places at once, is it possible that all electrons are that same one? More than thinking everything is connected, can we go one further and think that everything is the same thing? 

'Matter Waves' super positions connections between constellated nodes, spreading them out through space in multiple ways - an aesthetic exploration of these ideas.

metadata.name: Momentary #42
metadata.description:
Sometimes, life's troubles seem to be immense and endless. They make us run around in despair, helplessly looking in every direction in search of an answer.

It's tough to be in control of those situations until we understand that everything in our life is momentary, the good times are momentary and of course the bad ones.

We tend to forget that life finds its way and that we just need to hold enough to start to see a clear path to follow.

Life is momentary, the good times are momentary and of course the bad ones.

Hold enough.

There is a path to follow.

metadata.name: Floatrest #6
metadata.description:
Floating forests over the endless sky, where birds, trees, plants, roots, rocks and waterfalls share an ecosystem full of life and emotion.

You can see some rain clouds in the sky and the sun shining under the raindrops.

The earth is moving, the blocks are falling, but the trees are strong in their roots.

Welcome to 'Floatrest'.

----

# Features

- 7 tree palettes
- 17 different background colors
- 10 different terrain colors
- clouds
- vines
- roots
- plants
- waterfall
- birds
- sun / moon
- night
- dark mode
- monochromatic
- 2 different aspect ratios (square & portrait)
- Press "p" on live mode to save in PNG

This artwork requires processing power and is intended for laptops and desktops primarily. It may take some time to render.

----

July 2022, gpitombo

metadata.name: DisOrder #47
metadata.description:
Manual Dutch Auction (DA): 84 ¬∑ 56 ¬∑ 38 ¬∑ 26 ¬∑ 18  every 8 minutes.
Auction will stop changing price when non-reserves are fully minted.

/////////////////////////////////////////////////////

All that is, starts with Order.

Order attempts to evade entropy by following its own intrinsic patterns. Then, inevitably, there is change: an anomaly, a nudge that turns into a catalyst for widespread change.The momentum cannot be stopped.

Brief cycles build upon themselves, iterating and breaking into something new with each turn. Now, looking back, the accumulation of small divergences look like a leap, with trails of evolutionary decline casting tall shadows on the patterns that bore them.

The beauty of what this entropy creates, rises beyond chaos. It represents the past, and signals the future, and suddenly looks like a wild take on Order itself ‚Äì the true DisOrder of life.

metadata.name: an abstract concept #122
metadata.description:
I often try to duplicate my IRL analog abstract painting in code, and this, like my previous mint "a fleeting moment," is an attempt at that. Or it started that way. As is usual with such things, it quickly took on a life of its own. 

The algorithm itself consists of three layers of the main particle abstraction, which comes in five different styles, and roughly eight layers of the "texture," which comes in three styles. The palette consists of the background color and three colors for the particle algorithm. The texture is always drawn with the first of those three colors (the "base" color.) 

The result is indicative of my normal painting style (I almost always use three color layers over a background color, and paint with a spatula, palette knife, or cake knife) but is its own unique look.

metadata.name: GuilCity #208
metadata.description:
GuilCity is the beginning of an exciting journey bringing Guillaume Cornet‚Äôs densely-packed cities into the generative realm with the help of Matthew‚Äôs (@frostbitten‚Äôs) magic touch.

Matthew‚Äîwith his background in coding and animation‚Äîenables a new opportunity to experience these cities like never before. Numerous elements from vehicles to characters and even architecture have been given life. Interact with the city (computer mouse only): poke and peek around (even behind) in this active search & find journey! 

Each generative city fills the composition with the type of whimsical, expressive elements and characters you‚Äôve come to know Guil for. What kinds of wacky features have you discovered yet?

‚Äî

The tech behind this project utilizes the highly compressed WEBP image format in order to provide so many full-color options. This format is great, but unfortunately Safari on desktop/laptop must be upgraded to at least version 14 and macOS to at least version 11 Big Sur to use it.

The animation system for this project was created from scratch with additional help from the PIXI.js library for individual mesh animations.

‚Äî

To find out more about your GuilCity, copy your unique operation hash and place it at the end of the following url:
‚Ä¢ https://my.guil.city?fxhash=
(for example: https://my.guil.city?fxhash=ooezL8cffNJGSc4TfNQp3u3WnDpkg8J3zFRczLuumceoYU5QYPs)

‚Äî


The entire process has been a learning experience for both of us, adapting and exploring the many possibilities to interact with each others‚Äô skills and ideas.

We really enjoyed building this project together and are excited as we invite you to take a dive into your very own urban playground!

Merci √† tous! Cheers!
  - Guillaume Cornet, Matthew Seremet
